bel Baer", "w": "106940"}, {"t": "Fine Brown Frame", "c": "Guadalupe Cartiero", "w": "106941"}, {"t": "Blues (unspecified)", "c": null, "w": "105210"}, {"t": "Crescendo in Drums", "c": "Cozy Cole", "w": "106946"}, {"t": "Hurry On Down", "c": "Cab Calloway", "w": "106939"}, {"t": "Caravan", "c": "Duke Ellington", "w": "3061"}]}], "works_created": [{"t": "Crescendo in Drums", "w": "106946"}], "quotes": [], "about_quotes": [{"speaker": "Billy Taylor", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 1.0, "evidence": "So he introduced me to Cozy and he hired me, and Don Bias… Billy Taylor on bass, Billy Taylor who used to work with Duke Ellington, myself on piano, Tiny Grimes on guitar, Don Bias on tenor, and Cozy Cole on drums. We played a Broadway show...", "doc_title": "Billy Taylor — Smithsonian Jazz Oral History", "collection": "si", "url": "https://amhistory.si.edu/jazz/Taylor-Billy/Taylor_Billy_Transcript.pdf"}, {"speaker": "Sammy Price", "relation": "in music group with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Pete Brown and Vic Dickenson and...who was the drummer? Cole. ... That thing that I did with Milt Hinton was called 'Barrelhouse Blues and Boogie Woogie.' ... With Vic Dickenson, Cozy Cole, Pete Brown and Jonah Jones.", "doc_title": "67460_Sammy Price oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/67460/"}, {"speaker": "Marty Grosz", "relation": "knows of", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "Lionel Hampton I remember was one of the ones. “Rhythm, Rhythm” by Lionel Hampton, with Johnny Hodges and Allan Reuss was on it and Cozy Cole and Jess Stacey and everything.", "doc_title": "Marty Grosz interviewed by Monk Rowe, Los Angeles, California, September 4, 1995", "collection": "hamilton", "url": "https://litsdigital.hamilton.edu/collections/object/marty-grosz-interviewed-monk-rowe-los-angeles-california-september-4-1995"}, {"speaker": "Trummy Young", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "I remember I did a recording with Cozy Cole, myself, Coleman Hawkins, Earl Hines... Cozy was the drummer. And it came out under Cozy's name.", "doc_title": "52300_Trummy Young oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/52300/"}, {"speaker": "David Albert Francis", "relation": "mentor of", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "I took lessons from Cozy, when I was learning how to read... Now Cozy was responsible for me getting interested in learning about rudiments", "doc_title": "61521_David Albert Francis oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/61521/"}, {"speaker": "Walter P. Thomas", "relation": "collaborated with", "confidence": 0.95, "evidence": "I recorded a lot with Cozy when he was recording. And I used to write the arrangements... Cozy and I got a studio together.", "doc_title": "68429_Walter P. Thomas oral history interview", "collection": "rutgers", "url": "https://rucore.libraries.rutgers.edu/rutgers-lib/68429/"}]}